TY  - JOUR
T1  - Effects of Ownership Structure and Control on Corporate Productivity
AU  - Hill, Charles W. L.
AU  - Snell, Scott A.
Y1  - 1989/03/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256418
DO  - 10.5465/256418
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 25
EP  - 46
VL  - 32
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study developed and tested a model that attempts to describe the influence of ownership structure on productivity differences between firms. We theorized that diversification, investment in R&D, capital intensity, and ownership structure all determine firm productivity. Ownership structure was proposed to affect productivity both directly and indirectly through the mediators of diversification strategy, R&D expenditure, and capital intensity. Results based on data from a cross-sectional set of 122 Fortune 500 firms suggested that ownership affects a firm's posture toward diversification and investment in R&D. Those factors and capital intensity in turn explain differences in productivity between firms.
AB  - This study developed and tested a model that attempts to describe the influence of ownership structure on productivity differences between firms. We theorized that diversification, investment in R&D, capital intensity, and ownership structure all determine firm productivity. Ownership structure was proposed to affect productivity both directly and indirectly through the mediators of diversification strategy, R&D expenditure, and capital intensity. Results based on data from a cross-sectional set of 122 Fortune 500 firms suggested that ownership affects a firm's posture toward diversification and investment in R&D. Those factors and capital intensity in turn explain differences in productivity between firms.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256418
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256418
Y2  - 2026/04/24
