TY  - JOUR
T1  - Attentional Demand and Cost Responsibility as Stressors in Shopfloor Jobs
AU  - Martin, Robin
AU  - Wall, Toby D.
Y1  - 1989/03/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256420
DO  - 10.5465/256420
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 69
EP  - 86
VL  - 32
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Two studies were conducted to test for the effects of attentional demand and cost responsibility on psychological strain. One was a field experiment involving operators of computer-based manufacturing equipment, and the other was a cross-sectional investigation of employees in a wide range of jobs. The results showed increased strain only for those in jobs high on both attentional demand and cost responsibility. Implications for job design for new manufacturing technologies are discussed.
AB  - Two studies were conducted to test for the effects of attentional demand and cost responsibility on psychological strain. One was a field experiment involving operators of computer-based manufacturing equipment, and the other was a cross-sectional investigation of employees in a wide range of jobs. The results showed increased strain only for those in jobs high on both attentional demand and cost responsibility. Implications for job design for new manufacturing technologies are discussed.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256420
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256420
Y2  - 2026/04/24
